<TEXT>
president bush keeping the 
persian gulf crisis at the top of his agenda flew to germany today 
to meet with german chancellor helmut kohl in advance of the 
opening of a 34nation summit in paris 
bush was met here in a cold rain by kohl and the two leaders 
boarded a helicopter for a flight to speyer in kohls home region 
where bush was to attend an organ recital in speyer cathedral and 
speak in the town square 
kohl was then to take the us president to his home in nearby 
ludwigshafen 
afterwards bush was flying to paris for dinner with french 
president francois mitterrand at the elysee palace on monday bush 
will join soviet president mikhail s gorbachev in paris for the 
signing of a landmark treaty to slash nonnuclear weapons in 
europe nonnuclear weapons in europe 
the signing ceremony will be followed immediately by the opening 
of a threeday meeting of the 34nation conference of security and 
cooperation bringing former adversaries of the cold war together 
in a new era of reconciliation 
todays stop in germany retraces some sites visited by gorbachev 
last weekend when he visited kohl bush first will hear an organ 
recital at an 11thcentury cathedral in speyer and then go to 
kohls home in oggersheim for lunch a news conference is scheduled 
before the meeting ends 
aside from the gulf a prime topic for discussion was the 
deteriorating political and economic situation in the soviet union 
which is braced for a winter of extreme shortages of food and fuel 
kohl announced last week that germany will provide emergency 
food aid to moscow and he urged other western nations to do the 
same us officials said the bush administration is developing 
contingency plans to provide emergency supplies 
from the start of his visit to prague bush put a spotlight on 
the gulf crisis linking the past year of revolution in europe to 
the crisis in the persian gulf 
i have this feeling in my heart that no peoples understand 
better what is at stake in the gulf than czechs and slovaks bush 
said 
you know from your own bitter experience that the world cannot 
turn a blind eye to aggression you know the futility and vain hope 
that aggressors can be appeased he said 
president vaclav havel said czechoslovakias own history has 
taught us ample lessons about the consequences of appeasement 
onethird of czechoslovakias territory was ceded in 1938 to the 
nazis in an unsuccessful attempt to prevent adolf hitler from 
conquering other countries 
a huge crowd braved cold temperatures and biting winds to see 
bush place a wreath at a memorial in wenceslas square site of many 
turning points in czechoslovakias turbulent history czechoslovak 
television estimated the crowd at 150000 but us officials 
claimed the turnout was much larger 
america will not fail you in this decisive moment bush 
promised the crowd america will stand with you 
he delivered the same pledge earlier in a speech to the federal 
assembly and yet bush did not bring any major package of aid 
offering instead a modest package of incentives to spur us 
investment 
bush was unreserved in paying tribute to the reform movement 
that toppled czechoslovakias communist rule in a revolution that 
began last nov 17 
that is why i am here today we have not forgotten and the 
world will never forget what happened here in this square where the 
history of freedom was written the president assured the crowd 
</TEXT>
