jewish cemeteries in france former ku klux klan leader david duke 
making a strong bid for the us senate and neonazis in the 
pacific northwest he wonders 
if this happens when there are still survivors what will 
happen when were gone 
the world lost 11 million people of which 6 million were 
jews to think people look at that and still have that hate it 
leaves one completely aghast why why 
now a hotelier in vancouver british columbia he has spent much 
of the past seven years reminding people of the nazis slaughter of 
6 million jews 
he was one of several speakers being featured during the twoday 
conference that began sunday marking 45 years since the end of 
world war ii captive and free lessons of the holocaust for 
today and tomorrow was organized by the interfaith council on the 
holocaust which is devoted to preserving the memories and lessons 
of those years of genocide 
by the spring 1945 waisman at 14 had spent nearly onethird of 
his life in concentration camps the last eight months at 
buchenwald in germany he lost both parents and four brothers in 
the holocaust 
when us troops arrived to liberate the camp he recalled in a 
telephone interview last week he thought he was dreaming when two 
soldiers with brown skin approached he thought he was dreaming he 
had never seen black men 
in 1983 he saw pictures of soldiers in a magazine article about 
the liberators one of them was leon bass a former philadelphia 
high school principal who waisman learned was active as a speaker 
on the holocaust he was one of the black men waisman had seen 38 
years before 
waisman called bass who was a corporal in the 183d engineer 
combat battalion part of the pattons third army and they got 
together and talked for hours 
we have sort of shared a moment in time where we just glanced 
at each other waisman said and 40 years later we met again 
and became very close friends 
bass was at first dubious that waisman truly remembered him he 
certainly remembered no faces 
when i came into the camp i did not see him bass said i 
saw all the walking dead in front of me he was looking out the 
window all skin and bones 
bass said he has seen enough in 65 years not to be disheartened 
by current events 
if people dont stand up to racism we would go downhill he 
said maybe we havent moved as far ahead as we might have moved 
but if we hadnt tried we would be farther down the hill 
john raines the interfaith councils cochairman and a temple 
university religion professor said a rash of antisemitic 
incidents in europe made sunday and mondays conference more 
timely 
clearly what we are seeing in eastern europe is the revival of 
very ancient hatreds he said 
as the communist bloc dissolves he said people revert to old 
nationalistic loyalties and traditional religions 
an unfortunate part of those traditional religions in eastern 
europe and russia is antisemitism he said 
waisman who moved to western canada to get as far away as 
possible from europe and the memories broke nearly four decades of 
virtual silence in 1983 after hearing that a teacher in alberta was 
telling students the holocaust never happened he now speaks 
frequently on the subject 
you have no idea how gratifying it is waisman said i 
speak about the camps and i have to dig back into my memory its 
painful as hell but when you speak to the students and they 
come up afterward and they write you letters the pain is worth 
it 
</TEXT>
