<TEXT>
mikhail gorbachev enters the 34nation eastwest 
summit fresh from a major government crisis at home and with 
uncertain prospects for what could be a hungry and tumultuous 
soviet winter 
gorbachev said before leaving moscow that the conference on 
security and coopration in europe would be major landmark in the 
history of our continent 
but the real action was back in the soviet union 
on thursday gorbachev became the first soviet leader ever 
summoned before parliament to account for his failures and on 
friday he proposed a new government structure 
the disarray within the soviet empire could hardly contrast more 
sharply with the first csce summit that session held in helsinki 
in 1975 produced the socalled helsinki accords which defined the 
human rights obligations of the participants and ratified the 
presence of soviet ground forces and promoscow regimes throughout 
eastern europe 
soviet power and prestige may have reached their peak during 
that year it was the summer of the ussoviet joint space 
mission a few months after the inglorious american withdrawal from 
vietnam the year a prosoviet government came to power in angola 
a time when communists were strong in italy france and portugal 
for now gorbachev has turned his attention to the meeting in 
paris where the scheduled highlight is a treaty that ostensibly 
slashes eastwest conventional armies in europe 
the pact in fact consecrates the retreat of most soviet ground 
forces behind their own borders by the end of 1994 
the collapse of the soviet bloc over the past 15 months has 
outpaced conventional forces negotiations and diplomats already 
are talking about a followup treaty to keep up with events 
another highlight of the 34nation conference was to be the 
signing of a nonagression pact between the north atlantic treaty 
organization and the kremlinled warsaw pact this agreement too 
would have seemed impossible three years ago but today recognizes 
established fact 
gorbachev arrives in paris straight from rome one of the many 
west european capitals he has visited in the past month seeking 
financial and moral support 
president bush already has told officials to draw up plans to 
rush food to moscow if needed and british prime minister margaret 
thatcher commissioned a fund to convey british industrial knowhow 
to the soviet union 
no one knows whether such aid will bolster gorbachev 
confronting the revolt this week in the formerly tame supreme 
soviet legislature gorbachev announced not simply that he was 
dumping the unpopular prime minister nikolai ryzhkov but that he 
was changing the very structure of government 
the council of ministers that ryzhkov heads will be scrapped 
along with the newly created presidential council 
gorbachev announced plans to enhance the federation council a 
body that previously had little power but has the virtue of 
including representatives from the 15 soviet republics 
by boosting the power of the federation council gorbachev 
effectively embraced a proposal put forward by his rival russian 
president boris yeltsin to form a government made up of 
representatives from the 15 soviet republics 
gorbachevs solution however did not seem to move the soviet 
union closer to his stated goal of a government of laws rather than 
unchecked power and fit the pattern of his increasingly stopgap 
measures to prop up central power 
although the helsinki summit of 1975 ratified the borders of 
postwar europe those borders are again in flux the demolition of 
the berlin wall just over a year ago removed a frontier that two 
generations of soviet leaders struggled to preserve 
now the borders of the soviet union itself are threatened as 
the three baltic republics of lithuania latvia and estonia along 
with the caucasian republics of armenia and georgia seek outright 
independence and moldavian nationalists agitate to reunify with 
romania 
in russia by far the largest soviet republic yeltsin and his 
russian government are waging what promises to be a successful 
campaign for control of stateowned oil and gas fields as well as 
other natural and industrial resources 
the ukraine the second largest soviet republic is also getting 
restive and is likely to win enhanced rights if it agrees to 
gorbachevs proposal to sign a new treaty of union replacing the 
1924 charter that united the soviet republics 
despite the promise of western aid it is not clear what if 
anything bush and the other leaders will be able to offer the 
soviet union or whether there is anything they could do to bolster 
gorbachevs collapsing authority 
equals 
editors note bryan brumley moscow bureau chief for the 
associated press has covered soviet affairs since 1981 
</TEXT>
