police and troops armed with machineguns on sunday cleared sections 
of a strategic jungle road blocked 
for more than two weeks by protesters supporting the former contra 
rebels 
in a communique broadcast on radio and television late saturday 
president violeta chamorro said she had ordered the army to clear 
the rama road which connects the eastern caribbean coast with 
managua and western nicaragua 
the statement read by the information minister danilo lacayo 
indicated the government planned a crackdown on the protests that 
have left 24 people dead in the south and central regions of the 
country 
in her communique mrs chamorro also accused former contra 
leader aristides sanchez herdocia of plotting the recent protests 
she said he had orchestrated a broad plan against peace 
sanchez who is under arrest in managua was a director of the 
usbacked nicaraguan resistance that battled the former leftist 
sandinista government for nine years 
vice president virgilio godoy who is at odds with mrs 
chamorro met with 18 protesting mayors sunday and said the 
government should be responding to the protesters with political 
answers not arrests 
the government should seek a way to satisfy the popular 
demands without showing it is humiliated or that it is losing 
authority godoy told the mayors 
he called their actions a beautiful movement of civic 
patriotic and peaceful protest with a popular base he added that 
the government crackdown was intended to simplify and hide the 
responsibility of seeking solutions to the problems 
about 200 soldiers and police backed by helicopters on sunday 
were tearing down barricades on the strategic 200milelong 
highway where at least 13 barriers had been erected 
most of the troops were armed with automatic weapons and some 
rode in armored cars the operation was peaceful reporters at the 
scene said 
in her statement mrs chamorro said faced with the existence 
of this dangerous plan and the need to reestablish free 
transportation along the rama highway the government ordered 
the forces of public order to normalize transit with the 
total clearing of all of the highway 
the protesters want the government to fulfill promises of land 
and aid made to the former rebels they also want members of the 
sandinista opposition removed from key military and police posts 
the sandinistas still control security in nicargua despite 
losing a feb 25 election to mrs chamorro who took office in 
april rebels laid down their weapons in return for the promises of 
assistance 
but by the governments own figures barely 3000 of the 20000 
rebels have received land 
